Both methods are used to create a new table. The code example shows `newTable`, which is the correct method to use.
```ts
import { SimpleDB } from '@nshiab/simple-data-analysis';
const sdb = new SimpleDB();
const table = sdb.newTable('myTable');
await sdb.done();
```

The `loadData` method can handle different file formats. Replace 'csv' with the appropriate extension.
```ts
import { SimpleDB } from '@nshiab/simple-data-analysis';
const sdb = new SimpleDB();
const table = sdb.newTable('myTable');
await table.loadData('path/to/your/data.json');
await sdb.done();
```

It's important to call `done()` to release resources. Here's how to do it properly.
```ts
import { SimpleDB } from '@nshiab/simple-data-analysis';
const sdb = new SimpleDB();
// ... perform operations ...
await sdb.done();
```

Yes, you can create multiple tables by calling `newTable` multiple times.
```ts
import { SimpleDB } from '@nshiab/simple-data-analysis';
const sdb = new SimpleDB();
const table1 = sdb.newTable('table1');
const table2 = sdb.newTable('table2');
await sdb.done();
```

You can wrap the `loadData` call in a try-catch block to handle any potential errors.
```ts
import { SimpleDB } from '@nshiab/simple-data-analysis';
const sdb = new SimpleDB();
const table = sdb.newTable('myTable');
try {
  await table.loadData('path/to/your/data.csv');
} catch (error) {
  console.error('Error loading data:', error);
}
await sdb.done();
```

Simply provide the correct file path in the `loadData` method.
